				<div id=3D"bodyContent" class=3D"vector-body ve-init-mw-desktopArticleT=
arget-targetContainer" aria-labelledby=3D"firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-c=
ontainer=3D"">
					<div class=3D"vector-body-before-content">
							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><p class=3D"mw-empty=
-elt">
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:10_yr_old_Mastiff.JPG" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https:=
//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/10_yr_old_Mastiff.JPG/2=
50px-10_yr_old_Mastiff.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"177"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2030" data-file-height=3D"143=
7"></a><figcaption>Older dogs, similar to this 10-year-old <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neapolitan_Mastiff" title=3D"Neapolitan Mastiff">N=
eapolitan Mastiff</a>, often grow grey hairs on their muzzles, and some dog=
s grow grey hair all over.  Not all dogs gain grey hair when aging.</figcap=
tion></figure>
<p><b>Aging in dogs</b> varies from breed to breed, and affects the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dog" title=3D"Dog">dog</a>'s health and p=
hysical ability. As with humans, advanced years often bring changes in a do=
g's ability to hear, see, and move about easily. Skin condition, appetite, =
and energy levels often degrade with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Geriatric" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Geriatric">geriatric</a> age. =
Medical conditions such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cancer"=
 title=3D"Cancer">cancer</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kidn=
ey_failure" title=3D"Kidney failure">kidney failure</a>, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthritis" title=3D"Arthritis">arthritis</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dementia" title=3D"Dementia">dementia</a=
>, and joint conditions, and other signs of old age may appear.
</p><p>The aging profile of dogs varies according to their adult size (ofte=
n determined by their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dog_breed" t=
itle=3D"Dog breed">breed</a>): smaller breeds have an average lifespan of 1=
0=E2=80=9315 years, with some even exceeding 18 years in age; medium breeds=
 typically live for 10 to 13 years; and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Giant_dog_breed" title=3D"Giant dog breed">giant dog breeds</a> have =
the lowest minimum lifespan, with an overall average of 8 to 13 years. The =
latter reach maturity at a slightly older age than smaller breeds, with gia=
nt breeds reaching adulthood at around two years old compared to the norm o=
f around 13=E2=80=9315 months for other breeds. The accelerated rate of gro=
wth required by the drastic change in size exhibited in giant breeds is spe=
culated by scientists at the American Kennel Club to lead to a higher risk =
of abnormal cell growth and cancer.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-1"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Terminology">Terminology</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAging_in_dogs&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Terminology"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:13-year-old_Cairn_Terrier.jpg" class=3D"mw-fi=
le-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/=
thumb/0/0c/13-year-old_Cairn_Terrier.jpg/250px-13-year-old_Cairn_Terrier.jp=
g" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"244" class=3D"mw-file-element=
" data-file-width=3D"2052" data-file-height=3D"2000"></a><figcaption>A 13-y=
ear-old dog of a small breed, such as this <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Cairn_Terrier" title=3D"Cairn Terrier">Cairn Terrier</a>, would be=
 approximately 68 in equivalent human age, whereas a large breed would be a=
round 96.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The terms <i>dog years</i> and <i>human years</i> are frequently used wh=
en describing the age of a dog. However, there are two diametrically oppose=
d ways in which the terms are defined:
</p>
<ul><li>One common nomenclature uses "human years" to represent a strict ca=
lendar basis (365 days) and a "dog year" to be the equivalent portion of a =
dog's lifetime, as a calendar year would be for a human being. Under this s=
ystem, a 6-year-old dog would be described as having an age of 6 human year=
s or 40=E2=80=9350 (depending on the breed) dog years.</li>
<li>The other common system defines "dog years" to be the actual calendar y=
ears (365 days each) of a dog's life, and "human years" to be the equivalen=
t age of a human being.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-2"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By =
this terminology, the age of a 6-year-old dog is described as 6 dog years o=
r 40=E2=80=9350 human years, a reversal from the previous definition.</li><=
/ul>
<p>However, regardless of which set of terminology is used, the relationshi=
p between dog years and human years is not linear, as the following section=
 explains.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Aging_profile">Aging profil=
e</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAging_in_d=
ogs&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Aging profile=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>Dog age concepts can be summarized into three types:
</p>
<ul><li>Popular myth =E2=80=94 It is popularly believed that one human year=
 equals seven dog years.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-akc.org_3-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-akc.org-=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> This is inaccurate since dogs are able to reproduce from the =
age of 1.</li>
<li>One size fits all =E2=80=94 A rule of thumb is that the first year of a=
 dog's life is equivalent to 15 human years, the second year equivalent to =
9 human years, and each subsequent year about 5 human years.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-akc.org_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-akc.org-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> So, a dog age 2 is equiva=
lent to a human age 24, while a dog age 10 is equivalent to a human age 64.=
 This is more accurate but still fails to account for size/breed, which is =
a significant factor.</li>
<li>Size- or breed-specific calculators =E2=80=94 These try to factor in th=
e size or breed as well. These are the most accurate types. They typically =
work either by expected adult weight or by categorizing the dog as "small",=
 "medium", or "large".</li></ul>
<p>No one formula for dog-to-human age conversion is scientifically agreed =
on, although within fairly close limits they show great similarities. Resea=
rchers suggest that dog age depends on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/DNA_methylation" title=3D"DNA methylation">DNA methylation</a> which i=
s an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epigenetics" title=3D"Epigene=
tics">epigenetic</a> process. Epigenetic changes occur nonlinear in dogs co=
mpared to human.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxidative_stress" title=3D"=
Oxidative stress">Oxidative stress</a> appears to be a significant determin=
ant of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longevity" title=3D"Longevi=
ty">longevity</a> in small breed compared to large breed dogs.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Jimenez2018_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-Jimenez2018-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA_damage_(naturally_occurring)" title=3D"DNA da=
mage (naturally occurring)">Oxidative damage to DNA</a> can be measured by =
assessing the level of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/8-Oxo-2%27-=
deoxyguanosine" title=3D"8-Oxo-2'-deoxyguanosine">8-Oxo-2'-deoxyguanosine</=
a> in DNA.  Oxidative DNA damage measured in puppies was found to be higher=
 in larger dog breeds with shorter lifespans than in smaller breed dogs wit=
h longer life spans.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jimenez2018_5-1" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-Jimenez2=
018-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>  This result suggested that DNA repair mechanisms fail ea=
rlier in larger breed dogs so that more DNA damage is accumulated sooner in=
 these breeds leading to reduced longevity.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jimenez2018_=
5-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_=
dogs#cite_note-Jimenez2018-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Emotional maturity occurs, as with humans, over an extended period o=
f time and in stages. As in other areas, development of giant breeds is sli=
ghtly delayed compared to other breeds, and, as with humans, there is a dif=
ference between adulthood and full maturity (compare humans age 20 and age =
40 for example). In all but large breeds, sociosexual interest arises aroun=
d 6=E2=80=939&nbsp;months, becoming emotionally adult around 15=E2=80=9318 =
months and fully mature around 3=E2=80=934 years, although as with humans l=
earning and refinement continue thereafter.
</p><p>According to the UC Davis <i>Book of Dogs</i>, small-breed dogs (suc=
h as small <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terrier" title=3D"Terri=
er">terriers</a>) become <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geriatric=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Geriatric">geriatric</a> at about 11 years=
; medium-breed dogs (such as larger <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Spaniel" title=3D"Spaniel">spaniels</a>) at 10 years; large-breed dogs (s=
uch as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/German_Shepherd_Dog" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"German Shepherd Dog">German Shepherd Dogs</a>) at=
 8 years; and giant-breed dogs (such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Great_Dane" title=3D"Great Dane">Great Danes</a>) at 7 years.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Life_expectancy_by_breed">L=
ife expectancy by breed</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DAging_in_dogs&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit =
section: Life expectancy by breed"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Life expectancy usually varies within a range. For example, a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beagle" title=3D"Beagle">Beagle</a> (average=
 life expectancy 13.3 years) usually lives to around 12=E2=80=9315 years, a=
nd a Scottish Terrier (average life expectancy 12 years) usually lives to a=
round 10=E2=80=9316 years. The longest living verified dog is <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bluey_(long-lived_dog)" title=3D"Bluey (long-li=
ved dog)">Bluey</a>, an Australian Cattle Dog who died at 29 years. <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobi_(dog)" title=3D"Bobi (dog)">Bobi</a>=
, a male purebred <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rafeiro_do_Alent=
ejo" title=3D"Rafeiro do Alentejo">Rafeiro do Alentejo</a>, was claimed to =
have died at age 31 in 2023.
</p><p>Two of the longest living dogs on record, "<a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Bluey_(long-lived_dog)" title=3D"Bluey (long-lived dog)">Bl=
uey</a>" and "Chilla", were <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austra=
lian_Cattle_Dog" title=3D"Australian Cattle Dog">Australian Cattle Dogs</a>=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bluey_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-Bluey-7"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This has prom=
pted a study of the longevity of the Australian Cattle Dog to examine if th=
e breed might have exceptional longevity. The 100-dog survey yielded a mean=
 longevity of 13.41 years with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
tandard_deviation" title=3D"Standard deviation">standard deviation</a> of 2=
.36 years.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Pascal_Lee_Survey_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-Pascal_Lee_S=
urvey-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> The study concluded that while Australian Cattle Dogs a=
re a healthy breed and do live on average almost a year longer than most do=
gs of other breeds in the same weight class, record ages such as Bluey's or=
 Chilla's should be regarded as uncharacteristic exceptions rather than as =
indicators of common exceptional longevity for the entire breed.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-Pascal_Lee_Survey_8-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-Pascal_Lee_Survey-8"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A random-bred dog (also known as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Mixed-breed_dog" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mixed-breed dog">mo=
ngrel</a> or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutt_(dog)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mutt (dog)">mutt</a>) has an average life expecta=
ncy of 13.2<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"wh=
ite-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:C=
itation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This cla=
im needs references to reliable sources. (June 2023)">citation needed</span=
></a></i>]</sup> years in the Western world.
</p><p>Some attempts<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> have been made to determine the =
causes for breed variation in life expectancy.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Sorted_by_breed_or_life_exp=
ectancy">Sorted by breed or life expectancy</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAging_in_dogs&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Sorted by breed or life expectancy"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
