<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Factors_affecting_life_expe=
ctancy">Factors affecting life expectancy</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAging_in_dogs&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Factors affecting life expectancy"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Apart from breed, several factors influence life expectancy:
</p>
<ul><li>Frequency of feeding =E2=80=94 Researchers associated with the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dog_Aging_Project" title=3D"Dog Aging =
Project">Dog Aging Project</a> report that dogs that are fed just once dail=
y are healthier on average than dogs fed more frequently.  Dogs that receiv=
ed one meal per day had fewer disorders of their dental, gastrointestinal, =
musculoskeletal, kidney, and urinary systems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ogden_12-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dog=
s#cite_note-Ogden-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-13"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diet_(nutrition)" title=3D"Die=
t (nutrition)">Diet</a> =E2=80=94 There are some disagreements regarding th=
e ideal diet. Commonly, senior dogs are fed commercially manufactured <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Senior_dog_diet" title=3D"Senior dog di=
et">senior dog food diets</a>. However, at least two dogs died at 27 years =
old with non-traditional diets: a Border Collie who was fed a purely vegeta=
rian diet,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_=
in_dogs#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and a bull terrier cross fed primarily <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kangaroo_meat" title=3D"Kangaroo mea=
t">kangaroo</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emu_meat" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Emu meat">emu meat</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-fickl=
ing2004_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-fickling2004-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> They died only 2 years=
 and 5 months younger than the second oldest reported dog, Bluey.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spaying_and_neutering" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Spaying and neutering">Spaying and neutering</a> =
=E2=80=94 According to a study by the British Veterinary Association (autho=
r AR Michell is the president of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Royal_College_of_Veterinary_Surgeons" title=3D"Royal College of Veterina=
ry Surgeons">Royal College of Veterinary Surgeons</a>), "Neutered females l=
ived longest of dogs dying of all causes, though entire females lived longe=
st of dogs dying of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_causes=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Natural causes">natural causes</a>, with n=
eutered <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Male_dog" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Male dog">males</a> having the shortest lifespan in each cat=
egory."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-vetrec_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-vetrec-17"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Ne=
utering reduces or eliminates the risk of some causes of early death, for e=
xample <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyometra" title=3D"Pyometra=
">pyometra</a> in females, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tes=
ticular_cancer" title=3D"Testicular cancer">testicular cancer</a> in males,=
 as well as indirect causes of early death such as accident and euthanasia =
(intact dogs roam and tend to be more aggressive), but there might increase=
 the risk of death from other conditions (neutering in cited paper only sho=
wed an increase in the risk for prostate cancer but has not been repeated i=
n subsequent papers) in males, and neutered males might have a higher rate =
for urinary tract cancers such as transitional cell carcinoma and prostatic=
 adenocarcinoma.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Caution should be used when interpr=
eting the results of these studies. This is especially important when you c=
onsider the frequency of transitional cell carcinoma and prostate carcinoma=
 in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Male_dog" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Male dog">male dog</a> versus the chance an intact male dog wi=
ll succumb to death from roaming (hit by car or other injuries), benign hyp=
erplasia of the prostate causing prostatic abscesses or inability to urinat=
e (causing euthanasia if this does not resolve with therapy) or euthanasia =
due to fighting or aggression.</li></ul>
<dl><dd>Another study showed that spayed females live longer than intact fe=
males (0.8 years more on average) but, unlike the previous study, there wer=
e no differences between neutered and intact males. But both groups lived 0=
.4 years more than intact females.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-O'Neill_20-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_=
note-O'Neill-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd></dl>
<p>For more information, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neute=
ring#Health_and_behavioral_effects" title=3D"Neutering">Health effects of n=
eutering</a>.
</p><p>A major study of dog longevity, which considered both natural and ot=
her factors affecting life expectancy, concluded that:
</p>
<dl><dd>"The mean age at death (all breeds, all causes) was 11 years and 1 =
month, but in dogs dying of natural causes it was 12 years and 8 months. On=
ly 8 percent of dogs lived beyond 15, and 64 percent of dogs died of diseas=
e or were euthanized as a result of disease. Nearly 16 percent of deaths we=
re attributed to cancer, twice as many as to heart disease. [...] In neuter=
ed males the importance of cancer as a cause of death was similar to heart =
disease. [...] The results also include breed differences in lifespan, susc=
eptibility to cancer, road accidents and behavioral problems as a cause of =
euthanasia."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-vetrec_17-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-vetrec-17"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p></dd></dl>
<p>In 2024, a study published in the journal <i>Scientific Reports</i> invo=
lving 584,734 British dogs across over 150 breeds revealed that larger bree=
ds and those with flattened faces tended to have shorter average lifespans =
compared to smaller dogs and breeds with elongated snouts. Female dogs were=
 found to live slightly longer than male dogs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_=
note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Effects_of_aging">Effects o=
f aging</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAgin=
g_in_dogs&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Effects=
 of aging"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>In general, dogs age in a manner similar to humans. Their bodies begin t=
o develop problems that are less common at younger ages, they are more pron=
e to serious or fatal conditions such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Cancer" title=3D"Cancer">cancer</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Stroke" title=3D"Stroke">stroke</a>, etc. They become less physic=
ally active and less mobile and may develop joint problems such as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthritis" title=3D"Arthritis">arthritis<=
/a>. They also become less able to handle change, including wide climatic o=
r temperature variation, and may develop dietary or skin problems or go <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deafness" title=3D"Deafness">deaf</a>=
. In some cases <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urinary_incontinen=
ce" title=3D"Urinary incontinence">incontinence</a> may develop and breathi=
ng difficulties may appear.
</p>
<dl><dd>"Aging begins at birth, but its manifestations are not noticeable f=
or several years. The first sign of aging is a general decrease in activity=
 level, including a tendency to sleep longer and more soundly, a waning of =
enthusiasm for long walks and games of catch, and a loss of interest in the=
 goings on in the home."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-canismajor_22-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-cani=
smajor-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup></dd></dl>
<p>In studies of cognitive abilities in aging dogs, it has been shown that =
qualities such as problem-solving, boldness and playfulness tend to decline=
 with age. However, in tasks involving high motivation and low physical dem=
ands, older dogs have learned to perform a new task just as well as younger=
 ones. In old age dogs may develop dementia, which is associated with <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amyloid-beta" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Amyloid-beta">amyloid-beta</a>, a misfolded <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Protein" title=3D"Protein">protein</a> that has been observ=
ed in both dogs and humans.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ogden_12-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-Ogden-=
12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>The most common effects of aging are:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_=
note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Loss of hearing</li>
<li>Loss of vision (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cataract" titl=
e=3D"Cataract">cataracts</a>)</li>
<li>Decreased activity, more sleeping, and reduced energy (in part due to r=
educed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lung" title=3D"Lung">lung</=
a> function)</li>
<li>Weight gain (calorie needs can be 30=E2=80=9340% lower in older dogs)</=
li>
<li>Weakening of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immune_system" ti=
tle=3D"Immune system">immune system</a> leading to <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Infection" title=3D"Infection">infections</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skin" title=3D"Skin">Skin</a> =
changes (thickening or darkening of skin, dryness leading to reduced elasti=
city, loss or whitening of hair)</li>
<li>Change in feet and nails (thicker and more brittle nails makes trimming=
 harder)</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthritis" title=3D"Arthritis"=
>Arthritis</a>, dysplasia and other joint problems</li>
<li>Loss of teeth</li>
<li>Gastrointestinal upset (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stomac=
h_lining" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Stomach lining">stomach lining</a>=
, diseases of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pancreas" title=
=3D"Pancreas">pancreas</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consti=
pation" title=3D"Constipation">constipation</a>)</li>
<li>Weakness in muscles and bones</li>
<li>Urinary issues (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urinary_incont=
inence" title=3D"Urinary incontinence">incontinence</a> in both genders, an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prostatitis" title=3D"Prostatiti=
s">prostatitis</a>/straining to urinate in males)</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mammary_cyst" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Mammary cyst">Mammary cysts</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Mammary_tumor" title=3D"Mammary tumor">tumors</a> in femal=
es</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dementia" title=3D"Dementia">D=
ementia</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heart_murmur" title=3D"Heart m=
urmur">Heart murmurs</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diabetes_in_dogs" title=3D"Dia=
betes in dogs">Diabetes</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-24"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Importance_of_diet_in_aging=
">Importance of diet in aging</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DAging_in_dogs&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D=
"Edit section: Importance of diet in aging"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>By changing the nutrition of a dog's diet as it ages, certain ailments a=
nd side effects of aging can be ameliorated.
</p><p>Some proposed nutrients and ingredients in <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Senior_dog_diet" title=3D"Senior dog diet">senior dog diets=
</a> include:=20
</p>
<ul><li>Good sources of protein<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-25"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> to meet higher protein requirements<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-=
26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup></li>
<li>Glucosamine<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-:0-27"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> an=
d chondroitin sulfate<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_27-1" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-:0-27"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> to help maintain joint and bone health</li>
<li>Omega-3 fatty acids<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-28"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 for joint and bone health as well as maintaining immune system health</li>
<li>Calcium and phosphorus<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-29"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 for maintenance of bone structure</li>
<li>Beet pulp<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and flaxseed=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> for gastrointestinal heal=
th</li>
<li>Fructooligosaccharides and mannanoligosaccharides work to improve the h=
ealth of the gastrointestinal tract by increasing the number of "good" bact=
eria and decreasing the amount of "bad" bacteria<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cit=
e_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Appropriate levels of vitamin E and addition of L-carnitine to support =
brain and cognitive health<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_note-33"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
</li>
<li>Dietary antioxidants such as vitamin E.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_in_dogs#cite_not=
e-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup></li></ul>
